\b Develop Theoretical Argument for Presidential Partisan Heuristics\
\

\b0 Both reviewers felt that the original theoretical argument was underdeveloped. To address this concern we have significantly improved the discussion of our presidential partisan heuristics argument.\
\
- For the heuristic argument we advance the assumption that Fed Staff actually want to create a forecast that is as accurate as possible. This is plausible because they could both have a preference (because of professional socialisation, for example) and/or incentive (because of performance reviews). Though we don\'92t have direct evidence for either of these mechanisms directly, multiple pieces of research has found that Greenbook inflation forecasts are generally more accurate than private sector forecasts or other government forecasts. In the original version of the paper (and in this version as well) we discuss why a heuristic may not be updated. Primarily, as the extensive literature on heuristics shows they are not \'91conscious\'92 judgments.  As such, and as we document extensively as a major motivation of the paper, they are not being explicitly examined and therefore have not been adequately updated. If they were being examined and updated, then they wouldn\'92t be pure heuristics, but would be rational expectations. The empirical consequence of this is that presidential partisan errors would decrease or even disappear over time.    \
\
We have clarified in the discussion that the partisan heuristics theory does not assume that Fed Staff have a particular partisan or even an inflation preference. Instead it makes the argument that they incorrectly intuit the effect presidents from different partisan backgrounds have on inflation.\
\
- Our alternative theories challenges the assumption that their forecasts are not driven by partisan or inflation preferences and that they act on these preferences essentially in an information game with FOMC policy makers (who also have partisan and/or inflation preferences). In the partisan preference theory they have both a partisan and inflation preferences. In the monetary expectations theory they have a strong price stability preference, but not a partisan preference. \
\
Deciding which approach is more plausible is then the focus of our empirical investigations. \
\
There is another possibility that we do not explicitly examine. The persistence of the heuristic over the observation period may be due to a partisan preference rather than a heuristic then. This is implausible. Extending Arel-Burdock and Clark (2013) in the partisan preference theory, we posited that they would likely want to change information around elections rather than across entire presidencies (assuming that economic outcomes are more likely to effect electoral outcomes 6-12 months before an election as found by Gelman and King (1993)). Otherwise they would be creating long lasting deviations from their (presumably low) inflation preference in order to have very little effect on their partisan preference. For example, if there was a Republican president, and Fed Staff (or based on pressure from the FOMC) wanted to create information that would justify low interest rates then they would want to do this close to elections. Otherwise, they would be creating the conditions for low interest rates for a four year period, thus increasing inflation beyond their ideal point for a period of time that was unnecessarily long for helping Republicans stay in power. \
\
The possibility that they have a Democratic presidential preference has not been discussed in the literature. Furthermore, the results wouldn\'92t support such as story (a) it\'92s not that Democrats want high inflation and (b) having high interest rates seems like a counter-intuitive way to win elections, especially given what we know from the electoral business cycle literature. We would be happy to develop our discussion of this in the paper if requested.\
\
- We have also expanded the discussion of how the Fed Staff relate to the FOMC. Primarily showing that Greenbook forecasts are presented before FOMC meetings and that the FOMC spends a considerable amount of time discussing them.  \
